Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
8:52 AM; Case called for Hearing. Prosecuting attorney Andrew Nesheim in court for the State of Wisconsin.   Defendant Jennifer A Huber in court.  Court notes the matter is before the Court for status of counsel.  Defendant advises she still has not retained counsel yet, she went back to the Public Defender's office and did not qualify and has picked up and has completed a petition for court appointed attorney.  Court approves the petition, and orders repayment at the rate of $100.00 per month commencing 09/15/2022.  Court will adjourn for status of counsel.
Hearing scheduled for September 26, 2022 at 08:30 am.
Hearing on August 29, 2022 at 08:30 am.

08:37 AM; Case called for Hearing.   Defendant Jennifer A Huber in court.  Andrea M Will appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court inquires if the defendant has retained private counsel.  Defendant advises she is having issues financially and is not able to retain private counsel.  Court will have the defendant report back to the public defenders office to see if based on her circumstance changes she now qualifies, and if not she can always file a new petition for court appointed attorney.  Court adjourns for continued status of counsel.  Hearing scheduled for August 29, 2022 at 08:30 am.
Effective August 1, 2022, this case is assigned to Branch 7 Judicial Vacancy, pursuant to 22-SO-04(67).

Hearing on June 27, 2022 at 09:00 am.

08:43 AM; Case called for Hearing.  Defendant Jennifer A Huber in court.  Christian Farina appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court inquires if the defendant plans to represent herself in this matter.  Defendant advises that she does want an attorney, she previously filed a petition for court appointed attorney but was found to not be indigent.  Court reviews the petition and still finds the defendant does not qualify for a court appointed attorney.  Court advises the defendant she will need to retain private counsel.  Court adjourns for status of counsel in about 30 days.  Hearing scheduled for June 27, 2022 at 09:00 am.
